**3.1) Document design.** Since each spaceship has exactly one crew, and (under the simplifying assumption) each astronaut belongs to only one crew, the 1:1 spaceship–crew relationship and the 1:N crew–astronaut relationship can both be **embedded** inside the spaceship document — this is the natural "contains" access pattern (fetch a spaceship and its whole crew in one read):
```json
{
  "_id": ObjectId("..."),
  "name": "Dragonstar",
  "version": "v2.0",
  "price": 45000000,
  "seats": 6,
  "fuel_capacity": 1200,
  "crew": {
    "name": "Alpha Crew",
    "astronauts": [
      {
        "personal_id": "A001",
        "name": "Jane",
        "surname": "Doe",
        "birth_date": ISODate("1985-04-12"),
        "role": "engineer",
        "hiring_date": ISODate("2015-06-01")
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

**3.2)**
```javascript
db.spaceships.aggregate([
  { $match: { name: "Dragonstar" } },
  { $unwind: "$crew.astronauts" },
  { $project: { _id: 0, name: "$crew.astronauts.name" } }
])
```

**3.3)**
```javascript
db.spaceships.aggregate([
  { $match: {
      $expr: { $gte: [ { $size: "$crew.astronauts" }, 5 ] }
  } },
  { $match: {
      "crew.astronauts": {
        $elemMatch: {
          role: "engineer",
          $expr: { $eq: [ { $year: "$$this.hiring_date" }, 2015 ] }
        }
      }
  } },
  { $project: { _id: 0, name: 1, version: 1 } }
])
```
*(If the driver/MongoDB version does not support `$$this` inside `$elemMatch`, an equivalent approach is to `$unwind` the astronauts, filter with `role: "engineer"` and `$year(hiring_date) == 2015`, then `$group` back by spaceship and keep only spaceships whose original crew size is ≥ 5.)*

**4.1) Mapping.** `name` and `type` are short, exact-match, enumerable-ish values used for filtering/aggregation/sorting → `keyword`. `description` is free text meant to be searched/analyzed → `text`. `coordinates` is a geo point.
```json
PUT /destinations
{
  "mappings": {
    "properties": {
      "name":        { "type": "keyword" },
      "coordinates": { "type": "geo_point" },
      "description": { "type": "text" },
      "type":        { "type": "keyword" }
    }
  }
}
```

**4.2) Query.** Both "travel" and "solar system" must appear in `description` (must clauses), destinations named "Mars" are excluded (must_not on the keyword field), and `type: planet` boosts relevance without being mandatory (should clause):
```json
GET /destinations/_search
{
  "query": {
    "bool": {
      "must": [
        { "match": { "description": "travel" } },
        { "match_phrase": { "description": "solar system" } }
      ],
      "should": [
        { "term": { "type": { "value": "planet", "boost": 2.0 } } }
      ],
      "must_not": [
        { "term": { "name": "Mars" } }
      ]
    }
  }
}
```
